ford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Nazeing, Essex, England":"Nazeing, Essex, Engleska, United Kingdom","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1243–Aft 1270":"1243–po 1270","1243–1270":"1243–1270","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1267–1307":"1267–1307","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1221–Female":"1221–Zesnulá","1267":"1267","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","Aft 1270":"po 1270","Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Nazeing, Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom","Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Nazeing, Essex, England":"Nazeing, Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1243–Aft 1270":"1243–efter 1270","1243–1270":"1243–1270","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1267–1307":"1267–1307","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1221–Female":"1221–Afdød","1267":"1267","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","Aft 1270":"efter 1270","Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Nazeing, Essex, England":"Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1243–Aft 1270":"1243–na 1270","1243–1270":"1243–1270","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1267–1307":"1267–1307","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1221–Female":"1221–Overleden","1267":"1267","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","Aft 1270":"na 1270","Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Nazeing, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Nazeing, Essex, England":"Nazeing, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1243–Aft 1270":"1243–after 1270","1243–1270":"1243–1270","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1267–1307":"1267–1307","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1221–Female":"1221–Deceased","1267":"1267","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","Aft 1270":"after 1270","Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Nazeing, Essex, England":"Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wright","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a craftsman or maker of machinery, mostly in wood, of any of a wide range of kinds, from Middle English and Older Scots <i>wriht</i>, <i>wright</i>, <i>wricht</i>, <i>writh</i>, <i>write</i> (Old English <i>wyrhta</i>, <i>wryhta</i>) ‘craftsman’, especially ‘carpenter, joiner’. The term is found in various combinations (for example,   Cartwright   and   Wainwright  ), but when used in isolation it often referred to a builder of windmills or watermills. This surname is also very common among African Americans."],"variants":[{"name":"Wrights","meanings":["(1997: 103;2007: 204; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wright  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Wrightsman","meanings":["Probably English (although no longer found in Britain), meaning‘servant of the wright’ (see   Wright  )."]},{"name":"Cartwright","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): occupational name from Middle English <i>cart(e)</i> ‘cart’ + <i>wright(e)</i> ‘craftsman’ (Old English <i>cræt</i> or Old Norse <i>kartr</i> + Old English <i>wyrhta</i>), for a cartwright, a maker of carts.","Variant of   Courtright  , a surname of Dutch origin."]},{"name":"Wrightson","meanings":["English (northern England, especially Durham): patronymic from   Wright  , meaning ‘son of the wright’."]},{"name":"Right","meanings":["(2007: 493; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wright  ."]},{"name":"McWright","meanings":["Scottish or Irish: Gaelic patronymic with the English and Scots occupational term   Wright  , meaning ‘son of the wright’. The name is possibly a part translation of   McIntyre  , which fully translates as ‘son of the wright’."]},{"name":"Wrightman","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>wright</i> ‘craftsman’ (see   Wright  ) + <i>man</i> ‘man’, denoting someone who assisted a craftsman."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert William Wright was born in 1243, in Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord John William Wrighte, was 23 and his mother, Mrs. John William Wright, was 22. He married Dorothy de Montfort. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1270, in his hometown."},"et":{"1243–Aft 1270":"1243–pärast 1270","1243–1270":"1243–1270","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1267–1307":"1267–1307","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1221–Female":"1221–Surnud","1267":"1267","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","Aft 1270":"pärast 1270","Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Nazeing, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nazeing, Essex, England":"Nazeing, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1243–Aft 1270":"1243–1270 jälkeen","1243–1270":"1243–1270","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1267–1307":"1267–1307","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1221–Female":"1221–Kuollut","1267":"1267","1311":"1311","1245":